figure comes into focus, offering a rare portrait of Kierkegaard the man. Often viewed by his contemporaries as a person who deliberately cultivated an air of mystery and eccentricity, Søren Kierkegaard (1813-1855) has been, then and now, a subject of great speculation. His startling attack on the established church, his broken engagement with a young woman from a respected family, and his searing criticisms of literary figures--from the editors of The Corsair to Hans Christian Andersen--are among the acts that brought him much notoriety during his short lifetime. Yet arriving at a sense of the philosopher's personality and motives behind his behavior has been a difficult task. He left no memoirs of autobiography, but in the enormous cannon of his published writings, the author and the person Søren Kierkegaard is problematically present in a welter of disguises. An indispensable path to understanding what he was like as a person, maintains Bruce Kirmmse, is through the observations of his contemporaries. These accounts, ranging from the writings of Meïr Aron Goldschmidt, editor of The Corsair, to the recollections of Kierkegaard's fiancée, are organized around the major episodes of the philosopher's life. They enable us to glimpse, among many things, his spiritual and intellectual development, to get a sense of what it was like to be the object of his friendship or his wrath, and to examine various persons' opinions about his relationship with his young fiancée. The memories of this woman, Regine Olsen, who later married Fritz Schlegel, are among the most moving passages: they reveal her profound suffering, her personal understanding of Kierkegaard, and the satisfaction she ultimately felt, knowing that "he took her with him into history." This collection of first-hand accounts invites the reader to compare and interpret a wealth of fascinating stories, and in the end forms an intriguing "do-it-yourself" biography for both the scholar and general reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Philosophers.2bisacsh  aAalborgposten.  aAgerskov family.  aAndrae, Hansine.  aArentzen, Kristian.  aBeck, Frederik.  aBoesen, Emil.  aBrandes, Georg.  aBrosboll, Anna.  aBrøchner, Hans.  aClausen, Julius.  aCollett, Camilla.  aCollin, Henriette.  aDamkier, Jens Emil.  aFcedrelandet.  aFenger, Emil,.  aFeuerbach, Ludwig.  aHage, Johannes.  aHall, Carl Christian.  aHamilton, Andrew.  aHammerich, Angul.  aHansen, Peter.  aHoffding, Harald.  aIpsen, Harald Peter.  aJohansen, Niels.  aKant, Immanuel.  aKarup, Wilhelm Ignatius.  aKnudsen, Jakob.  aKoch, Carl.  aLevin, Israel.  aLindberg, Elise.  aLofting, Marguerite.  aLund, Holger.  aMeyer, Raphael.  aMourier, Hanne.  aNeiiendam, Robert.  aNielsen, Frederik.  aOlsen, Terkild.  aPaulli, Just Henrik.  aPlato.  aPloug, Hother.  aReitzel, Theodor.  aRørdam, Catrine.  aSchorn, Willy.  aSocrates.  aSodring, Julie Weber.  aSoro Academy.  aVidebech, Nanna.  aVisby, Carl Holger.  aWelding, Frederik.  aWolff, August.  aZinck, Otto.1 aKirmmse, Bruce H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLaursen, Virginia R.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691221885zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691221885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691221885.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  a